  "answer": "Viṣṇu Smṛti chapter 30 does not contain verses on the duties of the householder toward guests. Chapter 30 (work slug: unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8) is entirely about when Vedic study is forbidden — forbidden days, forbidden circumstances (eclipses, storms, impurity, battle, etc.), and the relationship between teacher and student (verses Vi_30.1–Vi_30.47).\n\nThe verses on the householder's duties toward guests (atithi) are found in Chapter 67 (Vi_67.28–Vi_67.46). Key verses there include: the householder must take utmost care in worshiping a guest (atithi) who arrives in the evening (Vi_67.28–29); he must not keep an atithi without feeding him (Vi_67.30); the atithi is to the householder as the husband is to women (Vi_67.31); a guest whose hopes are turned away takes the host's merit and leaves his sin (Vi_67.33); a Brahmin staying one night is an atithi (Vi_67.34); Kshatriyas may be fed after Brahmins eat (Vi_67.36); Vaishyas and Shudras arriving as guests should be fed with servants out of compassion (Vi_67.37); friends should be fed with the wife (Vi_67.38); a married daughter, maiden, sick person, and pregnant woman should be fed before the atithis (Vi_67.39); the husband and wife eat last from what remains (Vi_67.41); worship of an atithi surpasses even Vedic study, Agnihotra, sacrifice, and austerity (Vi_67.44); and in the evening and morning one should give the atithi a seat, water, food according to ability, lodging, a bed, foot-anointing, and a lamp (Vi_67.45–46).",
